answers.body_markdown:
Those header are indeed populated from that converter. It delegated to the `typeMapper`:

    this.typeMapper.fromClass(message.getPayload().getClass(), headers);

Where `DefaultJackson2JavaTypeMapper` has a logic around the mentioned `__TypeId__` header to add:

	public void fromJavaType(JavaType javaType, Headers headers) {
		String classIdFieldName = getClassIdFieldName();
		if (headers.lastHeader(classIdFieldName) != null) {
			removeHeaders(headers);
		}

		addHeader(headers, classIdFieldName, javaType.getRawClass());

That `getClassIdFieldName()` is `AbstractJavaTypeMapper.DEFAULT_CLASSID_FIELD_NAME` by default. 

So, with your current combination of the `ByteArraySerializer` and `ByteArrayJsonMessageConverter` there is no way to prevent that header to appear in the `ProducerRecord`. Unless you inject a custom `Jackson2JavaTypeMapper` with overridden `fromJavaType()` with an empty body.

You really can avoid it with a `DefaultKafkaHeaderMapper` and its `setMapAllStringsOut(true)` and there won&#39;t be that `spring_json_header_types` extra header if all headers you are going to send is `String` or already a `byte[]`.

See this ctor `DefaultKafkaHeaderMapper(ObjectMapper objectMapper, String... patterns)` and provide only those headers which you really need to send.

As was explained by @artem-bilan, it&#39;s not that easy to get rid of the `__TypeId__` when using `ByteArraySerializer` and `ByteArrayJsonMessageConverter`. So, I used `JsonSerializer` and `MessagingMessageConverter` instead.
Below is my configuration which produces Kafka events without any magic headers.
```java
@TestConfiguration
public static class TestKafkaProducerConfig {

    @Bean
    public KafkaTemplate&lt;String, MyEvent&gt; kafkaTemplate(
            @Value(&quot;${kafka.consumer.my-topic-name}&quot;) String topicName, EmbeddedKafkaBroker embeddedKafka) {

        var template = new KafkaTemplate&lt;&gt;(producerFactory(embeddedKafka));
        template.setDefaultTopic(topicName);

        // Use SimpleKafkaHeaderMapper which does not add the json types header, `spring_json_header_types`.
        // The mapAllStringsOut when set to true, all string-valued headers will be converted to byte[] using
        // the charset property (default UTF-8).
        var headerMapper = new SimpleKafkaHeaderMapper();
        headerMapper.setMapAllStringsOut(true);

        var messageConverter = new MessagingMessageConverter();
        messageConverter.setHeaderMapper(headerMapper);

        template.setMessageConverter(messageConverter);
        return template;
    }

    @Bean
    public ProducerFactory&lt;String, MyEvent&gt; producerFactory(EmbeddedKafkaBroker embeddedKafka) {
        return new DefaultKafkaProducerFactory&lt;&gt;(producerConfig(embeddedKafka));
    }

    public Map&lt;String, Object&gt; producerConfig(EmbeddedKafkaBroker embeddedKafka) {
        Map&lt;String, Object&gt; props = KafkaTestUtils.producerProps(embeddedKafka);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, JsonSerializer.class);
        props.put(JsonSerializer.ADD_TYPE_INFO_HEADERS, false);
        return props;
    }
}
```

